{"questionId":"17410","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"H\">\n  <mi>H</mi>\n</math></span> is a connected, planar graph, with <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"v\">\n  <mi>v</mi>\n</math></span> vertices, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"e\">\n  <mi>e</mi>\n</math></span> edges and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n</math></span> faces. Every face in <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"H\">\n  <mi>H</mi>\n</math></span> is bounded by exactly <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"k\">\n  <mi>k</mi>\n</math></span> edges.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Explain why <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"2e = kf\"> <mn>2</mn> <mi>e</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>k</mi> <mi>f</mi> </math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>counting the edges around every face gives <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"kf\"> <mi>k</mi> <mi>f</mi> </math></span> edges&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>but as every edge is counted in 2 faces&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\" \\Rightarrow kf = 2e\"> <mo stretchy=\"false\">⇒</mo> <mi>k</mi> <mi>f</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mi>e</mi> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17410","referenceCode":"19N.3.AHL.TZ0.Hdm_4b.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Explain why 2 e = k f .","paper":"3","level":"HL","questi